'''Banyan days''' are a British naval tradition that has changed meaning over the years. It originally was used to name that day of the week where no meat was served on  board ship. It now is used to describe a picnic or cookout for the ship's crew.The term is borrowed from the Banyans in the East Indies, a cast that eat nothing that had life.


